echo '<div class="mk-prose">';
echo '<p class="mk-muted" style="margin-top:0;">Key topics about the Mkomigbo project — mission, approach, and future.</p>';
echo '<h2>Why Knowledge Preservation Matters</h2>';
echo '<p>Every generation that passes without documenting oral traditions, community histories, and lived experiences represents an irreversible loss. Mkomigbo exists to slow and reverse that process — creating a permanent, accessible record that belongs to the community it documents.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Challenge of Igbo Documentation</h2>';
echo '<p>The Igbo present a particular documentation challenge. Their precolonial society was decentralized — no single archive, no central court, no unified administrative record. Knowledge was held in oral tradition, in the memories of titled men and women, in ritual practice, and in community consensus. Colonization disrupted these systems without replacing them adequately.</p>';
echo '<h2>Our Approach to Contested History</h2>';
echo '<p>Much of Igbo history is contested — especially the civil war, the slave trade, and the question of political sovereignty. Mkomigbo does not pretend these contests do not exist. We present evidence, acknowledge disagreement, and where knowledge is incomplete or disputed, we say so clearly. We do not suppress uncomfortable truths.</p>';
echo '<h2>The Role of the Diaspora</h2>';
echo '<p>The Igbo diaspora — in the UK, USA, Canada, Australia, and across Africa — carries a significant portion of Igbo cultural memory. Mkomigbo is built to serve diaspora communities as much as home communities. Much of our content is written by, and for, people who grew up between worlds.</p>';
echo '<h2>What We Are Building Toward</h2>';
echo '<p>The current platform is a foundation. Over time we intend to expand into multimedia content — oral history recordings, documentary references, photographic archives, and community-contributed materials. The goal is a living, growing knowledge commons that no single institution owns or controls.</p>';
